1. List 5 common hardware issues that can cause network problems in a typical office setup, and for each, describe one symptom that helps identify it.
=>
#Faulty Ethernet Cable
Symptom: Intermittent or no connectivity on a specific PC, with link lights off or flickering on the NIC and switch port, while other devices on the same switch work fine.
#Failing Network Switch Port
Symptom: One or more devices connected to particular ports lose connectivity or show very slow speeds, while devices on other ports function normally (often visible via switch LED status).
#Overheating or Failing Router
Symptom: Frequent random disconnections across the entire network, high latency, or the router's WAN/Internet light blinking irregularly or staying off.
#Power Supply Issues on a Switch/Router
Symptom: Device powers on but ports show no activity (no link lights), or the device randomly reboots, causing widespread outages for connected devices.
#Damaged or Loose Wi-Fi Access Point Antenna/Module
Symptom: Weak or no wireless signal in specific areas of the office, with devices showing "limited connectivity" or very low signal strength despite being close to the AP.


2. Open Cisco Packet Tracer or any network simulator, set up a small network with 3 PCs, 1 switch, and 1 router, and intentionally disconnect one device. Use the simulator's troubleshooting tools to identify which device is faulty and document the steps you took.
=>Add devices: 3 PCs , 1 Switch , 1 Router .
Connect them: PC0, PC1, PC2 → Switch (FastEthernet ports). Switch → Router . Configure basic IP addressing.
Configure Router with a default gateway and enable routing. Test full connectivity with ping from all PCs to each other and to the router.
Intentionally introduce a fault: Disconnect the cable from PC1 to the Switch 
Troubleshooting steps in the simulator:
Use the Packet Tracer "Simulation" mode to send ICMP packets from PC1 → observe failures.
Check LED status on devices.
Run ipconfig on PCs and show interfaces / show ip interface brief on Switch/Router via CLI to see "down/down" status.
Use the "Troubleshoot" tools or hover over devices to see link status.
Identification: The faulty/disconnected device shows no link light and failed pings, while others succeed. Reconnect or no shutdown the port to restore connectivity.

3.Create a troubleshooting checklist for diagnosing slow internet issues in a home WiFi network, including at least 8 steps covering both hardware and software checks.
=>Check physical connections: Ensure the modem/router Ethernet cable is securely plugged in and undamaged. 
Verify ISP modem lights are normal.
Router status lights: Look at the router — power, WAN, and WiFi lights should be solid (not blinking rapidly). Reboot the router (unplug 30 seconds).
Run speed test: Use speedtest.net or fast.com on a wired device first, then wireless. Compare against your ISP plan.
Check WiFi signal strength: Move closer to the router; check for interference .
Device WiFi settings: Forget the network and reconnect; ensure you're on the 5GHz band if available (less interference).
Run ping test: Open Command Prompt/Terminal → ping 8.8.8.8 -n 20 and ping google.com. High latency/packet loss indicates ISP or router issue.
Check for bandwidth hogs: Look at connected devices for unknown devices or heavy downloads/streaming.
Software checks: Update router firmware, scan for malware, disable VPN/proxy temporarily, check DNS .
4.You receive a complaint that a user cannot access Instagram and YouTube on their laptop, but WhatsApp Web works fine. Write down the first 5 troubleshooting steps you would perform to identify if the issue is with hardware, software, or network configuration.
=>
Verify basic connectivity: Confirm the laptop has internet .
Test other browsers/devices: Try opening Instagram/YouTube in an incognito window, different browser (Chrome vs Edge), or another device on the same network to rule out browser-specific issues.
Check DNS resolution: Flush DNS (ipconfig /flushdns), try changing DNS servers to Google (8.8.8.8) or Cloudflare (1.1.1.1) in network adapter settings. Many site-specific blocks are DNS-related.
Inspect for software blocks: Check firewall/antivirus settings, parental controls, or any proxy/VPN extensions that might selectively block video/streaming sites. Disable them temporarily.
Hardware/Network config check: Run Windows Network Troubleshooter, check for MTU issues  (netsh interface ipv4 show subinterfaces), or test with a wired connection if possible to isolate WiFi driver vs. broader network problems.
